1️⃣ Angular Services – “Why did you use services?”
Interviewer may ask:

Why do we use services in Angular?
What did you put inside services?

Your answer:

In Angular, services are used to separate business logic from UI components.
I used services mainly for:

Calling backend REST APIs

Managing shared state like authentication and environment selection

Reusing logic across multiple components

Example (what you actually did):

AuthService → login, register, store token, expose user observable

EnvService → manage DEV / TEST / PROD globally

ApiService → fetch APIs, create API, filter APIs

Why interviewers like this:

👉 Shows clean architecture, maintainability, testability


2️⃣ HttpClient – “How do you call backend APIs?”
Interviewer may ask:

How do you make REST API calls in Angular?

Your answer:

I use Angular’s HttpClient because it:

Supports observables

Automatically handles JSON

Works well with interceptors and error handling

Example explanation:

I used GET, POST, PUT, DELETE depending on the operation.
For example:

POST for login and register

GET for listing APIs and subscriptions

Bonus line (very good):

I never call HttpClient directly from components.


3️⃣ Observables & BehaviorSubject – This is IMPORTANT
Interviewer may ask:

Why did you use Observables?
What is BehaviorSubject?

Your answer:

Angular uses Observables for async data like HTTP responses and shared state.
I used BehaviorSubject when I needed:

The latest value immediately

And future updates automatically

Example (what you really did):

user$ in AuthService

env$ in EnvService

For example, when the user logs in, the header, sidebar, and footer automatically update without page reload.

One-liner:

BehaviorSubject is useful when multiple components need the same reactive state.


4️⃣ Router, RouterLink & Navigation – Routing mastery
Interviewer may ask:

How did you handle navigation in Angular?

Your answer:

I used Angular Router for client-side navigation.

routerLink for template navigation

router.navigate() for programmatic navigation (after login, logout, etc.)

Example:

After successful login, I navigated the user to the dashboard using router.navigate(['/app/manage-apis']).

Route parameters:

I used route parameters for pages like subscription details (/subscription/:id) and accessed them using ActivatedRoute.


5️⃣ Guards (AuthGuard, AdminGuard) – Security question
Interviewer may ask:

How did you protect routes?

Your answer:

I used Angular Route Guards to restrict access based on authentication and role.

AuthGuard → checks if user is logged in

AdminGuard → checks if role is ADMIN

This prevents unauthorized users from accessing protected routes even if they manually type the URL.

Very strong line:

Guards work at routing level, so protected components are never even created.

6️⃣ ChangeDetectorRef – Advanced / senior signal
Interviewer may ask:

Have you ever used ChangeDetectorRef?

Your answer:

Yes. I used ChangeDetectorRef when UI updates didn’t reflect immediately due to async operations or zoneless optimizations.

Example:

After login or environment change, I manually triggered change detection using markForCheck() to ensure header and sidebar updated correctly.

Important:

I don’t use it everywhere — only when needed.

7️⃣ Error Handling – Real-world question
Interviewer may ask:

How do you handle API errors?

Your answer:

I handle errors at subscription level and show user-friendly messages.
I avoid exposing backend error details directly to users.

Example:

401 → “Invalid credentials or account doesn’t exist”

0 (network error) → “Backend not reachable”

I also stop loaders using finalize() to avoid infinite loading.

8️⃣ Debugging in Angular – They LOVE this
Interviewer may ask:

How do you debug Angular applications?

Your answer:

I use multiple approaches:

console.log() to inspect data flow

Browser DevTools → Network tab to inspect API requests

Check status codes (401, 403, 500)

Angular error stack traces for routing or DI issues

Bonus:

I also use Postman to test APIs independently before integrating frontend.

9️⃣ Postman & Swagger – Backend coordination
Interviewer may ask:

How do you test APIs before using them in Angular?

Your answer:

I use Postman to:

Test request payloads

Verify responses and status codes

Validate authentication tokens

If Swagger is available, I use it as API documentation and contract reference.

🔟 Authentication Flow – End-to-end clarity
Interviewer may ask:

Explain your login flow.

Your answer (clean & confident):

User submits credentials → Angular service sends POST request → backend returns JWT → token stored securely → user state updated using BehaviorSubject → UI reacts automatically → user redirected.

